Sep 8 2005	Not bad but not great. 2 star.	This hotel was a shock to us after travelling from Hong Kong and staying in five star luxury there. I will start with the positive aspects. The staff is very friendly and speaks fair to good english. The on site restaurants had a good choice of food for both breakfast and dinner, and the service there was friendly and very good. For the price the hotel charges, this may be a good property for those looking to save a little on lodging. There is no Western standard here, but this may be good for travelers whom want to escape that and feel what a local hotel in China is like. The lobby is somewhat comfortable to sit and have a drink and watch people come and go. There is a theatre and two gift shops in the lobby. This hotel appears to cater to many European travelers. As for the negative aspects, the hotel is far from any tourist interests. There is, however, a subway station near by. It was a 10-15 minute cab ride to Tiananmen Square and the Forbidden City. One couldn't walk to much of anything. As soon as you leave the hotel property, you may be approached by street vendors trying to sell something. They are however easy to say &quot;no thank you&quot; to and will leave you alone very shortly. The area surrounding the hotel can make a traveler feel a bit apprehensive to venture out on his or her own. The area doesn’t feel that safe and seems a little poor. Simply crossing the street near the hotel, and in Beijing, can be quite a challenge, especially for those not used to traffic chaos and a seemingly free for all rush. Our room was very outdated, worn out and a little dirty. The hotel feels like it is stuck in the 60's as far as design is concerned.If we return to Beijing someday, we would certainly not stay here again	
